I’m not very familiar with how New York City tabs work, but the fact that one person has to foot the whole bill and everyone else has to pay that person separately is kind of an annoying feature because other places in New York City Don’t have that. After looking at many reviews for inexpensive Thai restaurants in Brooklyn, I selected Joya as it was rated very highly in several websites. Ten of us went to Joya expecting a great dining experience. But we were highly disappointed. First of all, the lightning was so dim that we had a tough time reading the menu. There were a few candles but they went out after a while. After a bit of struggle and with the help of several pairs of eyes, we found what we wanted and ordered the items. Spicy noodles, Thai soup and fried rice were okay. But red and green curries had no flavor and were and packed with cucumbers and other vegetables that had no taste. Service was terrible. Every time we needed our waiter, we couldn’t find him and had to leave the table and fetch him. They also didn’t have fried ice cream, a standard Thai dessert. When I asked for the bill, the waiter handed me a small piece of paper which turned out to be the bill. Even a hole in the wall, gives you the bill inside a small padded folder. When I was trying to estimate how much tip I should give, upon closer inspection I discovered that they had already added a 20% gratuity. The customer is not allowed to decide how much to tip given the level of service. I have been to many inexpensive Thai restaurants in Manhattan and Queens which  are very good to excellent. I don’t understand why Joya has such a high rating. I am never going back there again. And I would certainly recommend that you don’t either.
